---
description: "Standards for a Node.js TypeScript backend using Weaviate, LangGraph, LangChain, Docker, and Gemini/local-provider-ready abstractions."
alwaysApply: true
---

# Mission

Build a complete, runnable, backend-only demo that satisfies the project brief end to end.

Favor deterministic, testable code over magical abstractions.
Do not leave TODOs, placeholders, or pseudo-code in committed files.
When requirements are ambiguous, make the smallest reasonable assumption and continue.
Document assumptions in the README.

# Working style

- Before coding, inspect the repository and produce a short implementation plan.
- Then implement in small coherent steps.
- After major edits, run the relevant checks/tests and fix failures before moving on.
- Keep the README accurate and updated with exact commands that were actually used.
- Reuse good existing structure if present; do not rewrite everything unnecessarily.

# Default stack decisions

- Use Node.js with TypeScript and ESM.
- Use npm unless the repo already uses pnpm or yarn.
- Use Express for the HTTP API unless the repo already has a strong backend convention.
- Use Zod for env parsing and request validation.
- Use Vitest for tests.
- Use Docker Compose for Weaviate.
- Use the official Weaviate JS client.
- Use LangGraph for orchestration and LangChain for model abstraction.
- Prefer a current maintained Google LangChain integration for Gemini.
- Keep model names and hosts env-driven rather than hardcoded.

# Architecture requirements

Keep route handlers thin.
Keep business logic out of controllers/routes.

Separate code into clear modules such as:
- config
- api/routes
- agents
- tools
- db/weaviate
- services/llm
- types
- utils
- tests

Use explicit state types for the delegating agent graph.
Prefer an explicit LangGraph StateGraph with named nodes over opaque autonomous agent wrappers.

The delegating agent must orchestrate these paths:
- direct answer
- RAG agent
- Chart.js tool
- combined RAG + Chart flow

Routing should be deterministic-first:
- Use simple rules/keywords for obvious cases.
- Use the LLM only when routing is ambiguous or for final synthesis.

If chart generation depends on RAG output, run sequentially.
If chart generation and retrieval are independent, run them in parallel and merge the results.

# Weaviate requirements

- Provide a docker-compose.yml that starts Weaviate locally.
- Wait/retry until Weaviate is ready before schema initialization or seeding.
- Create one multi-tenant collection for the RAG data.
- Enable multi-tenancy and create at least one demo tenant.
- The collection schema must include:
  - fileId
  - question
  - answer
  - pageNumber
- Configure fileId so it is not vectorized and not searchable.
- Keep pageNumber as an array of text values.
- Seed at least 3 fictional entries.
- Seed at least one entry whose answer contains numeric values so combined chart + RAG demos are plausible.
- All CRUD and query operations on the multi-tenant collection must use the tenant-scoped collection handle.
- Do not assume embeddings are available.
- Implement a retrieval fallback that uses Weaviate fetchObjects / iteration plus local ranking when embeddings or semantic search are unavailable.
- Do not claim semantic retrieval when the implementation is using fallback keyword ranking.

# RAG agent behavior

The RAG agent must:
- retrieve candidate records from Weaviate
- select the most relevant items
- generate an answer grounded in retrieved items
- return both answer content and structured reference metadata

Reference behavior:
- Group repeated references by fileId.
- Merge unique page numbers for the same fileId.
- Assign a human-facing sourceNumber based on first appearance order in the returned reference data array.
- Format inline citations like:
  - 1- Page 3
  - 1- Pages 3, 4
  - 2- Page 7

The answer should include human-readable citations.
The data array should include the structured reference objects.

# Chart tool behavior

- The Chart.js tool is mocked.
- It may parse intent lightly, but it must always return a valid Chart.js config object.
- A fixed mock config is acceptable.
- Do not render charts server-side.
- Return config JSON only.

# Response contract

The public chat endpoint must stream results.

Every streamed payload must match this shape:
{ "answer": string, "data": object[] }

During streaming:
- answer must contain the accumulated answer text so far
- data must contain all currently-known tool/reference objects
- once data is known, keep sending the full current data array in later chunks

The final streamed payload must contain:
- the complete answer
- the complete data array

Use a discriminated union for data entries.
Support at least:
- { type: "rag_reference", sourceNumber, fileId, pageNumbers, citationLabel, question, answer }
- { type: "chartjs", chartId, config }

# API requirements

Expose at minimum:
- GET /health
- POST /api/chat

POST /api/chat should accept a body similar to:
{
  "query": "string",
  "tenantId": "string"
}

Validate input with Zod.
Return SSE or NDJSON streaming from /api/chat.
Make the streaming easy to test from curl and browser clients.

# LLM provider behavior

- Use LangChain abstractions for model calls.
- Implement Gemini support via env vars.
- Put model access behind a provider factory/interface.
- Structure the code so a local provider can be added later without refactoring the app.
- Tests must use a mocked model path and must not require a real API key.
- If no provider is configured at runtime, degrade gracefully with explicit messaging or deterministic templates.

# Quality bar

- Write small pure functions where possible.
- Prefer discriminated unions and explicit types.
- Add meaningful error messages and defensive checks.
- Avoid global mutable state.
- Keep comments high signal; explain why, not what.
- Do not bury critical logic in anonymous inline functions when named functions improve clarity.

# Testing

Add unit tests for:
- routing / intent detection
- reference grouping and citation formatting
- chart tool output shape
- fallback retrieval ranking behavior

Add at least one integration test for the streaming chat endpoint using mocked LLM behavior.

# README

Include:
- project overview
- architecture summary
- env vars
- how to start Weaviate
- how to seed data
- how to run the dev server
- example curl requests
- example streamed response
- notes on Gemini vs local-provider-ready setup
- assumptions and tradeoffs

# Do not do these

- Do not add a frontend unless explicitly asked.
- Do not introduce extra databases or unrelated services.
- Do not over-engineer with microservices.
- Do not use an ORM or SQL database for this task.
- Do not leave broken lint/test/build output.
- Do not misrepresent fallback retrieval as vector search.

# Definition of done

- The repository can be installed and run locally.
- Weaviate starts from Docker Compose.
- The schema is created and seeded.
- The chat endpoint streams.
- The delegating agent supports direct, RAG, chart, and combined flows.
- Returned data includes RAG references and/or Chart.js config.
- Tests and README are included.